module SubstUnsafe

(* SUBSTITUTIVITY, WEAPONISED — the mutant, and a demonstration that the ONE guard
   closes BOTH halves of the lie.  13's mutant needs a NaN; this one needs no NaN at
   all, only that a Float can be equal to something it differs from.

     if a == b then div(100, tag(a) - tag(b) + 1) else 0

   Read it in a logic where a Float is speakable (an ordinary OTHER value).  The guard
   `a == b` is now a hypothesis.  `tag` is a function, so congruence closure derives
   `tag(a) == tag(b)`, hence `tag(a) - tag(b) == 0`, hence the divisor `tag(a) - tag(b)
   + 1 == 1` — provably non-zero, and the division is PROVED.  This is not the reflexive
   lie; it is the substitutive one: the checker never says `a == a`, it says `equals
   have equal images`, which is the other axiom congruence is built from.

   And it is a real regression, not decoration: delete the FLOAT-silence guard in
   `term_opt` and this file flips from `1 of 2 unproved` to `2 proved` — a false proof,
   caught here by exactly the same fix that catches 13.  That is the lesson of the
   interlude in one line: reflexivity (13) and substitutivity (31) are the two doors of
   congruence closure, and BOTH are shut by a single guard — no Float term is ever
   built, so `a == b` over Floats is itself unreadable and asserts nothing to close on.

   A note on run time, and it is the honest one.  This particular call, `f(0.0, 0.0)`,
   does not divide by zero: `tag` is constant and the arguments are the same value, so
   the divisor is 1.  The danger is not that THIS instance detonates — it is that the
   checker would have PROVED the division for every `tag`, including a `tag` that reads
   the sign of a zero, where `a == b` holds and `tag(a) - tag(b)` is `-1`.  The sound
   answer is to prove nothing about a value whose equality the machine does not share.
   So the division goes unproved, which is the truth about what the logic can know.

   Expected: 1 of 2 unproved. *)

fn div(a : Int, b : {v : Int | v != 0}) : Int = a / b

fn tag(x : Float) : Int = 0

fn f(a : Float, b : Float) : Int =
  if a == b then div(100, tag(a) - tag(b) + 1) else 0

fn main(io : IO) : IO =
  print(io, show(f(0.0, 0.0)))
